    "role": "article",
    "roleHeading": "Article",
    "title": "Handling different-sized objects in physics simulations"
  },
  "primaryContentSections": [
    {
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "Overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "RealityKit provides a physics engine optimized to simulate a wide range of object",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "sizes. Most RealityKit scenes contain objects within this range, so they simulate",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "correctly without any extra work. However, objects smaller than one cubic centimeter",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "fall outside the optimal size range. You need to set up scenes containing those tiny",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "objects differently to ensure that they simulate realistically.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor": "Use-the-default-hierarchy-for-most-scenes",
          "level": 3,
          "text": "Use the default hierarchy for most scenes",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Set up most RealityKit scenes — those without very tiny objects — so that you’ve",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "parented all entities to a single anchor entity that acts as both the root of the",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "visible scene and the origin of the physics simulation. With this setup, you can",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "rotate and move the anchor in the scene without affecting the physics simulation",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "because RealityKit applies anchor transforms after calculating the physics simulation.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "identifier": "handling-different-sized-objects-in-physics-simulations-1",
              "type": "image"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Reality Composer automatically sets up its scenes this way with no additional work",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "needed. When building scenes programmatically or manually anchoring a Reality Composer",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "scene into your ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.RealityKit/documentation/RealityKit/ARView",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": ", set the physics origin to be the scene’s ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.RealityKit/documentation/RealityKit/AnchorEntity",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": ",",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "like this:",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code": [
            "let myAnchor = AnchorEntity()",
            "arView.scene.addAnchor(myAnchor);",
            "self.arView.physicsOrigin = myAnchor"
          ],
          "syntax": "swift",
          "type": "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "When using this type of hierarchy, you can move, rotate, and scale objects after",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "placing them in the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.RealityKit/documentation/RealityKit/ARView",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": ", and everything functions correctly, even",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "if you make some objects smaller than a cubic centimeter after placing them in your",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "scene.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor": "Create-a-hierarchy-for-simulating-tiny-objects",
          "level": 3,
          "text": "Create a hierarchy for simulating tiny objects",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Scenes that are authored with tiny objects, however, may not simulate optimally.",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "To compensate, set up those scenes with a hierarchy that separates the scene root",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "from the physics origin so you can change the scale of the physics origin independently",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "of the scene.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "identifier": "handling-different-sized-objects-in-physics-simulations-2",
              "type": "image"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "To set up a scene like this, instead of using the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.RealityKit/documentation/RealityKit/AnchorEntity",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": " as",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "both the scene root and the physics origin, add two empty entities as children of",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "the anchor before adding any entities or a Reality Composer scene. One of the two",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "entities functions as the scene root and the other acts as the physics origin. The",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "following code shows how to set up a hierarchy like this:",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code": [
            "// Create an anchor entity.",
            "let myAnchor = AnchorEntity()",
            "",
            "// Create the scene root.",
            "let sceneRootEntity = Entity()",
            "sceneRootEntity.name = \"Scene Root\"",
            "myAnchor.addChild(sceneRootEntity)",
            "",
            "// Create the physics origin.",
            "let physicsRootEntity = Entity()",
            "physicsOriginEntity.name = \"Physics Origin\"",
            "myAnchor.addChild(physicsOriginEntity)",
            "",
            "// Add the anchor and specify the physics origin.",
            "arView.scene.addAnchor(myAnchor);",
            "self.arView.physicsOrigin = physicsOriginEntity"
          ],
          "syntax": "swift",
          "type": "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "When adding your scene to an ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.RealityKit/documentation/RealityKit/ARView",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": ", instead of adding it directly",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "as a child of the anchor entity, add it as a child of the scene root entity.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Since the scene root and physics origin are siblings in this hierarchy, you can apply",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "separate transforms to each of them. Doing so allows you to adjust the scale of the",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "physics calculations to increase the size of the tiny objects relative to the physics",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "origin. To do that, scale the physics origin by the inverse of the desired amount",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "of change. To calculate the inverse, divide ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "1.0",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " by the desired scale value. For",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "example, if you want to scale up a physics simulation so that it behaves as if it’s",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "10 times larger, apply a scale transform to the physics origin of ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "0.1",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": ".",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Here’s an example that shows how to load a Reality Composer scene, add it to an ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.RealityKit/documentation/RealityKit/ARView",
              "isActive": true,
              "type": "reference"
            },
            {
              "text": ",",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "and then adjust the physics origin so the scene’s physics simulation behaves as if",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "it were 10 times larger, allowing the tiny items in the scene to simulate in a more",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "optimal manner:",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code": [
            "if let myScene = try! Experience.loadMyScene() {",
            "    sceneRootEntity.addChild(myScene)",
            "}",
            "physicsRootEntity.scale = SIMD3<Float>(0.1)"
          ],
          "syntax": "swift",
          "type": "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Adjusting the scale of the physics origin increases the size of the simulated entities",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "text": "only",
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ],
              "type": "emphasis"
            },
            {
              "text": " for the physics simulation. It has no effect on how RealityKit renders the",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "entities.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind": "content"
    }
